    "boxscore_url": "https://www.goairforcefalcons.com/sports/baseball/stats/2026/unlv-rebels/boxscore/24127",
    "recap_url": "https://www.goairforcefalcons.com/news/2026/3/14/baseball-takes-both-games-of-twin-bill-to-sweep-unlv-in-first-mw-series",
    "recap_headline": "United States Air Force Academy",
    "recap_text": "U.S. AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo., -\nAir Force baseball (6-11, 3-0) had quite the day taking the twin bill, 18-16 and 15-11, to sweep UNLV (13-8, 0-3) in their first Mountain West series of the season on Saturday at Erdle Field. Across the doubleheader, the Falcons racked up 33 runs off 32 hits while the pitchers totaled 16 strikeouts.\nAir Force 18, UNLV 16\nThough the Falcons led for much of the game, it wasn't until\nLuke Elmore\nrecorded a three-run walk-off home run that the win was secured. The first baseman went 3-for-6 with five RBIs, a double, and a homer.\nLandon Boyd\nposted a career-high six RBIs after launching a grand slam, as the Falcons finished the day with four home runs.\nGaines Estridge\ngot the start on the mound, pitching 5.1 innings with two strikeouts while allowing five earned runs. The first reliever,\nEthan Dillinger\n, struck out three Rebels and gave up two runs in 1.1 innings.\nDavis Rhyne\nand\nJoey Collier\neach recorded 0.2 innings before\nSam Hentges\nentered the game.\nMarcus Downing\n(2-0) threw the final inning and picked up his second win of the season.\nUNLV struck first, taking a 1-0 lead in the top of the second inning.\nThe Falcons answered immediately in the bottom half of the inning to tie the game at 1-1.\nTripp Garrish\nled off with a single, stole second, and advanced to third on a bunt single by\nBlake Campbell\n. An RBI groundout from Boyd brought Garrish home.\nIn the top of the third, the Rebels regained the lead, moving ahead 4-1.\nAir Force responded with five runs to take its first lead of the day, 6-4.\nWyatt Hanoian\nreached on an error and advanced to second after Garrish drew a walk. Elmore doubled down the left-field line to score Hanoian. Campbell was then hit by a pitch to load the bases, setting up Boyd's grand slam that traveled 380 feet over the right-center wall.\nThe Rebels cut the deficit to one run in the top of the fifth, making it 6-5.\nThe Falcons exploded for five more runs in the bottom of the fifth to extend their lead to 11-5. Hanoian opened the inning with his first career home run, a 455-foot blast. Garrish drew another walk, stole his second base of the day, and was joined on base by Campbell, who was hit by a pitch. Boyd then singled through the right side to score Garrish before\nBrooks Burdine\nlaunched a 446-foot home run, his first career homer.\nUNLV added runs in the sixth and another in the eighth to close the gap to 11-8.\nElmore drove in another run with an RBI single in the bottom of the eighth to give the Falcons a 12-8 lead.\nThe Rebels surged ahead in the top of the ninth, scoring eight runs to take a 16-12 lead.\nFacing their final chance, the Falcons mounted an incredible comeback to walk off UNLV, 18-16. Pinch hitter\nCam Anstey\nand\nKayden Bradshaw\nreached base before\nWalker Zapp\ndelivered an RBI single that brought both runners home. After a mound visit, Hanoian singled to drive in Zapp. Garrish then drew another walk to set the stage for Elmore, who ended the game with a three-run walk-off homer, his second long ball of the season.\nAir Force 15, UNLV 11\nKayden Bradshaw\nled the Falcons' offense with a perfect 4-for-4 performance, hitting for the cycle and driving in two runs. Catcher\nWalker Zapp\nadded two runs, two hits, and three RBIs, while eight different starters recorded at least one RBI.\nRight-hander\nBowen Brantingham\ngot the start, striking out four batters in 2.2 innings but allowing eight earned runs. Freshman\nJordan Watkins\n(1-2) took over and delivered four strong innings of relief, striking out three while allowing no earned runs to earn his first collegiate victory.\nGunner Gilmore\npitched 1.1 innings in relief and allowed two runs before\nPatrick Davidson\nentered to close the final frame, striking out two batters to record his first save of the season.\nUNLV jumped out to an early 3-0 lead in the top of the first inning to begin the series finale.\nThe Falcons quickly answered, taking a 4-3 lead in the bottom half of the inning. Bradshaw drew a leadoff walk and advanced to second on a groundout. Zapp followed with a towering 486-foot home run, his fourth of the season, to score two runs. The next batter,\nTripp Garrish\n, drew a walk, stole second, and executed a double steal with\nLuke Elmore\nto put both runners in scoring position.\nCam Anstey\nthen singled up the middle to bring them both home.\nAir Force added another run in the bottom of the second to extend the lead to 5-3 after Bradshaw tripled and scored on a wild pitch.\nThe Rebels regained the lead in the top of the third and added another run in the fourth to move ahead 9-5.t\nAir Force responded with a five-run fourth inning to reclaim the advantage at 10-9.\nLandon Boyd\ndoubled and advanced to third on a balk before\nBrooks Burdine\nlifted a sacrifice fly to score him. Bradshaw followed with a double and came around to score on a single from\nBen Niednagel\n. After Zapp singled and\nWyatt Hanoian\nwalked to load the bases, Garrish drew a walk to force in a run. Elmore then delivered a single through the right side to drive in two more.\nBradshaw added to the Falcons' lead in the fifth inning with a two-run home run, pushing the score to 12-9.\nAir Force scored its final runs of the series in the bottom of the seventh, extending the lead to 15-9. Back-to-back singles from Burdine and Bradshaw, along with a walk to Niednagel, loaded the bases. Zapp brought home one run with a groundout, and Hanoian followed with a triple that cleared the bases.\nThe Rebels threatened in the top of the eighth but ultimately settled the final score at 15-11.\nAir Force returns to Erdle Field for a Monday matinee against St. Thomas on March 16 at 1 p.m. MT."
  },
